<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 10:16<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If69030e16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I6059a720933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>10.</label.designator><headtext>Remand</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94fa2c2ae1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>10:16.</label.designator><headtext>Choice of district for remand</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>This is one of the panel&apos;s simplest decisions. <eos/><bos/>It may remand an action only to the district in which it was pending at the time of transfer.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If69030e26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] The Panel may retransfer cases, although this is rarely done.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If69030e36b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Remand does not present an opportunity to consider selection of a new transferee district. <eos/><bos/>If a case is reassigned to a new district, it is done only as a transfer (or retransfer) under <cite.query w-src-number="0304914146" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I729ff2206b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407</cite.query>, and not as part of the remand power.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If69030e16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If69030e26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.</ital>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914146" w-serial-number="1977126499" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="933" ID="I729ee0b16b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Air Crash Disaster in Ionian Sea on September 8, 1974, 438 F. Supp. 932, 933 n.1 (J.P.M.L. 1977)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914146" w-serial-number="1976142595" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="797" ID="I729ee0b36b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Delta Airlines, Inc., Flight Attendant Weight Standards Litigation, 411 F. Supp. 795, 797 (J.P.M.L. 1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If69030e36b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Retransfer is discussed in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs8:7" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If69057f06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 8:7</cite.query> with special attention to tag-along actions. <eos/><bos/>Although the question arises most frequently when tag-along actions cause new parties and concerns to come before the Panel, retransfer can arise on a motion for remand. <eos/><bos/><ital>See, e.g.</ital>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914146" w-serial-number="1978124041" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="391" ID="I729fa4016b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re South Central States Bakery Products Antitrust Litigation, 462 F. Supp. 388, 391 (J.P.M.L. 1978)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 10:16<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
